V \u000a\u000a\u000aEyebrows were raised when Martin Scorsese\u2019s real-life drama was nominated for a Golden Globe for Best Motion Picture, Musical Or Comedy.
p1
aVAlthough the soundtrack (including covers of Goldfinger and Mrs Robinson) is excellent, and it is Scorsese\u2019s funniest film by some distance, Wolf is neither musical nor comedy, more a riotously dayglo Goodfellas.
p2
aVBeginning in a whir of crashing helicopters and tossed dwarves, it\u2019s a filthy, fizzy ride following the spectacular rise and predictable fall of 1980s stock market fraudster Jordan Belfort (Leonardo DiCaprio).
p3
aVBut between the cameos (Matthew McConaughey, Joanna Lumley, Spike Jonze), globetrotting (London, Las Vegas, Auckland) and endless debauchery, there\u2019s a scabrous joie de vivre that\u2019s impossible to resist.
p4
aVOne scene sees Belfort vividly miming anal sex while closing a sale with a clueless client.
p5
aVAnother has him and his colleagues enjoying themselves on a coke-and-hooker-filled private jet.
p6
aVMultiply that by 180 minutes and you have some idea what you\u2019re getting into.
p7
aVThough brilliantly written (by Boardwalk Empire\u2018s Terence Winter), acted and directed, Wolf is dangerously overlong.
p8
aVThis is especially galling because Belfort often speaks directly to the audience to speed the action on.
p9
aVCouldn\u2019t he have whizzed us through the details of his downfall the same way?
p10
aVThe only excuse is that the material is just too juicy to cut, and everyone, from a career-best DiCaprio, to his crack-smoking sidekick Jonah Hill, to Scorsese himself is having too good a time to stop.
p11
aVFor at least two of the three hours, you will be too.
p12
aVMaybe those Golden Globe guys were on to something after all.
