aVTurner."
p837
aVI\u2019m certainly not an expert on 19th century British painters, but I can imagine that "Mr. Turner" is made with such care that it could be a wonderful introduction to art students studying the life of Joseph Mallord William Turner (1775-1851).
p838
aVDirector Mike Leigh and actor Timothy Spall have painted their own masterpiece.
p839
aVTurner\u2019s genius was established early in his career, and Leigh chose to focus on the latter half of the artist\u2019s life when he became even better known and more eccentric.
p840
aVTurner\u2019s devotion to his ailing father is clear in the film.
p841
aVAs were the relationships with women that kept him unmarried, by choice, his entire life.
p842
aVLeigh\u2019s screenplay also captures Turner\u2019s artistic independence, both his stubbornness and epic vision.
p843
aVGreat accolades can be heaped on Spall\u2019s interpretation of Turner.
p844
aVDid the artist grunt, groan and speak in spurts?
p845
aVI don\u2019t know and don\u2019t care.
p846
aVSpall dives deep and fascinates with his performance.
p847
aVIt took me several minutes to adjust to his dialect, but I eventually heard every word spoken by this worthy actor.
p848
aVMost of the ensemble cast checks out as well.
p849
aVDorothy Atkinson generates sympathy as Hannah Danby, Turner\u2019s devoted housekeeper.
p850
aVMarion Bailey does an admirable job as Sophia Booth, Turner\u2019s landlady and eventual lover.
p851
aVShe made Turner\u2019s seaside home a peaceful, desirable retreat.
p852
aVPaul Jesson excelled as Turner\u2019s father.
p853
aVHe and Spall played well off each other.
p854
aVThe mutual love and devotion between these two characters was realized.
p855
aVThe costumes, the sets, the cinematography transport you magnificently to Turner\u2019s era.
p856
aVI learned about art history and the human condition.
p857
aVI\u2019m inspired to know more about the artist and see his works in person, thanks to Mike Leigh, his cast and crew.
p858
aVThank you. 
p859
aV Now proclaimed as Britain\u2019s greatest artist, his talent is the soul of Mike Leigh\u2018s new film, Mr. Turner.
p860
aVComing after his other historical dramas\u2014the effervescent Topsy-Turvy, about Gilbert and Sullivan, and the dreary, bleak Vera Drake, which focuses on an abortionist in the 1950s\u2014this is perhaps his most spare, yet illuminating film to date.
p861
aVHe\u2019s certainly picked a perfect subject: Turner was a bona fide genius who never stopped experimenting or challenging convention, yet, as Leigh shows, his personal life was a mess, including unhappy illegitimate children and a rather odd housekeeper who provided à la carte services for her boss.
p862
aVThough Leigh\u2019s film follows a basic chronological approach, starting when the artist is at the height of his fame, it is arranged as a series of vignettes rather than a completely fleshed out, plot-driven movie.
p863
aVAnd for someone as complex as J.M.W.
p864
aVTurner, that is perhaps the best way to capture the dichotomy of the man.
p865
aVCoddled by his father, who runs his household, sells his paintings and even mixes the valuable pigments and colours used to create those spectacular works of art, Turner is a crude, driven man comfortable in his selfishness.
p866
aVHis world revolves around his ability to translate three-dimensional vistas into two-dimensional paintings.
p867
aVHe thinks nothing of dropping everything, and everyone, for a painting excursion.
p868
aVIt\u2019s actor Timothy Spall who brings what could have been a two-dimensional caricature to life.
p869
aVSpall immersed himself in the Dickensian world of Victorian London, even spending two years learning to paint.
p870
aVHis every twitch, lumpen step and grunt\u2014dialogue is at an absolute minimum\u2014conveys more than the wordiest of scripts.
p871
aVAfter winning at Cannes, Spall is all but guaranteed to get an Oscar nomination.
p872
aVRelated reading: Brian D. Johnson\u2019s best films of 2014\u000aThe other force behind Mr. Turner who should earn an Oscar nod is Dick Pope, the movie\u2019s cinematographer, who turned film into a work that would rival any Turner painting.
p873
aVFrom the very first scene in the Dutch countryside, to the last of the dying artist, the lush visuals\u2014especially its raw landscapes and delicately gorgeous sunrises and sunsets\u2014celebrate the artist.
p874
aVTurner lived in a time of deprivation and enormous wealth, an era when constant work and graft was the only way the son of a barber could rise to be one of the art world\u2019s greats.
p875
aVYet, for all his achievements and financial security, the unpolished, slovenly genius constantly chafed against convention.
p876
aVThe scenes of Turner sizing up his competition, including John Constable, at the Royal Academy, are deliciously subversive.
p877
aVIronically, as his works become less recognizable and more and more evocative\u2014Rain, Steam and Speed: The Great Western Railway breathes the disruptive fury and power of the new-fangled trains\u2014his personal life became more pedestrian, even happy.
p878
aVHe settled down with a widow, Sophia Booth, who fussed over Turner with the same un-awed affection of his father.
p879
aVEven after his death, Turner was anything but normal: He gave most of his fortune away, and donated his collection of his own, best works to the nation.
p880
aVEven today, his namesakes\u2014the Turner Prize, for example\u2014conjures up images of innovation and experimentation.
p881
aVAs the Guardian stated, "If the sun is God, as Turner is supposed to have said, this incandescent painter was the sun\u2019s high priest and art is indebted to him."
p882
