aVWhatever the mutants can do, the Sentinels can do better.
p977
aVAnd, they use their new skills to kill the mutants, one by one.
p978
aVMagneto (Ian McKellen) and Professor Charles Xavier (Patrick Stewart), often enemies, unite in this dystopian future to send Wolverine (Hugh Jackman) back in time to keep Mystique (Jennifer Lawrence) from killing the Sentinels inventor.
p979
aVBolivar Trask (Peter Dinklage) was martyred by Mystique\u2019s bloodworks, prompting President Richard Nixon\u2019s approval of the Sentinels program.
p980
aVHow do you stop Mystique?
p981
aVMagneto and Xavier decide to send Wolverine back to 1973, using the time travel powers of Shadowcat (Ellen Page).
p982
aVHow do you tell such a complicated story stocked with so many characters without having the audience go crazy trying to keep up?
p983
aVGet the guy who\u2019s done it before many times, Bryan Singer.
p984
aVNot only is he a veteran of previous X-Men films, he knows how to handle complex plots (The Usual Suspects).
p985
aVOf course, a director is only good as his writer.
p986
aVAnd, Simon Kinberg gets huge kudos for making this breathtaking story jump from the page.
p987
aVFinally, the actors.
p988
aVNot only the truly talented thespians I mentioned previously.
p989
aVBut, how about a tip of the hat to James McAvoy (young Professor X) and Michael Fassbender (young Magneto) and a breakthrough performance by Evan Peters as Quicksilver.
p990
aVPeters is bright, hip and oh so likable as the mutant with the ability to run at supersonic speeds.
p991
aVOh, and a "Game of Thrones" alert.
p992
aVPeter Dinklage is interesting to watch as the chief villain, Trask.
p993
aVBut, this is the only role that could have been improved.
p994
aVIt\u2019s a bit of a one-note character, and that\u2019s not the fault of the excellent actor who plays Lord Tyrion on the popular HBO series.
p995
aV"X-Men: Days of Future Past" is one of the best films I\u2019ve seen so far in 2014.
p996
aVIt\u2019s more than just a super hero movie.
p997
aVIt\u2019s a true champion of summer fun.  
p998
aV \u000a\u000a\u000aHaving realigned the rom-com and feminised the bromance with the hilarious Bridesmaids, director Paul Feig now attempts to makeover the action-comedy with slightly more mixed success.
p999
aVFor while Sandra Bullock and Melissa McCarthy make for an engaging mismatched pair to rival Riggs and Murtagh and Foley and Rosewood, they\u2019re saddled with a predictable drug cartel plot that seems to needlessly stretch the running time by an extra 20 minutes.
p1000
aVThe central relationship initially also seems depressingly similar to McCarthy\u2019s earlier 2013 effort Identity Thief.
p1001
aVLuckily, after a while McCarthy\u2019s loose cannon (and her The Fighter-esque Boston family) and Bullock\u2019s by-the-book agent start to grow on you, particularly when given the chance to let loose on one another\u2019s fashion sense, hygiene and dating life.
p1002
aVBoth also get plenty of opportunities to showcase their adeptness at physical and visual gags, while a black humour approach to the action will have many cinema-goers wincing while doubled over with laughter.
p1003
aVThe Heat might lack the sheer balls-to-the-wall, gag-a-minute quality of The Other Guys or even the wacky charm of last year\u2019s 21 Jump Street remake, but it\u2019s both a reminder of Bullock\u2019s comedic talents and one of the best female comedic pairings since Tina Fey met Amy Poehler.
p1004
aV So, it\u2019s doubly disappointing that the producers went cheap and stupid on the script.
p1005
aVSandra Bullock plays her uptight FBI agent from "Miss Congeniality" and Melissa McCarthy is a slovenly Boston cop.
p1006
aVTogether, they look to take down a mysterious drug kingpin plaguing Bean town in "The Heat."
p1007
aVIt\u2019s refreshing to give us something new like a big-screen version of "Cagney and Lacey."
p1008
aVBut, when you bombard us with every cop-buddy cliché in the book, are we supposed to roll over and say it\u2019s pure genius?
p1009
aVNo, can\u2019t do it.
p1010
aVEverything\u2019s predictable.
p1011
aVBefore they even meet each other, they fight over a parking spot in front of the police station.
p1012
aVThey fight over the clothes they wear on the job.
p1013
aVThey wind up bonding and bust the bad guys, complimenting each other by the end.
p1014
aVIs it fun to see the morbidly obese McCarthy curse like a sailor nonstop for two hours?
p1015
aVNo.
p1016
aVIf writer Katie Dippold had been a bit more sparing, the verbal fireworks might have been more effective.
p1017
aVIs it fun to see Bullock NOT be able to curse for nearly two hours?
p1018
aVNo.
p1019
aVBut, we know that by the end she\u2019ll be up to speed and that\u2019s supposed to be hilarious.
p1020
aVNo, "The Heat" didn\u2019t miss a single cop-buddy cliché.
p1021
aVAll it did was place two women in the roles instead of two men.
p1022
aVKudos for doing that, but give the women something to work with.
p1023
aVYuk!  
p1024
aV The Dark Knight Rises, which opens next week, is the most hotly anticipated movie of the summer.
p1025
aVAnd yes, it lives up to the hype.
p1026
aVBut what\u2019s most astonishing is not Batman\u2019s new flying machine that zooms around skyscraper canyons, or a flirty Anne Hathaway poured into a skin-tight catsuit and stiletto boots, or a muzzled terrorist who looks like an S&M wrestler on steroids.
p1027
aVNo, the most breathtaking moment in the epic finale of the Batman trilogy is when Michael Caine weeps.
p1028
aVWhy?
p1029
aVThat would be a spoiler.
p1030
aVLet\u2019s just say the domestic bickering between Bruce Wayne (Christian Bale) and Alfred (Caine), his paternal butler, finally comes to an emotional head.
p1031
aV"Sir Michael Caine is always going to surprise you," says writer-director Christopher Nolan, on the phone from Los Angeles.
p1032
aV"Having worked with him on five movies, I knew he was going to bring something special to that scene.
p1033
aVBut when he performed it, it was absolutely gutting.
p1034
aVWe sat there in dailies and people were just sobbing."
p1035
aVDon\u2019t be surprised to see Caine honoured at the Oscars, or to see The Dark Knight Rises vie for Best Picture.
p1036
aVSome franchises simply peter out.
p1037
aVNolan\u2019s trilogy, like the Lord of the Rings and Harry Potter sagas, has an engineered momentum that builds to a monumental climax.
p1038
aVAfter Batman Begins (2005) and The Dark Knight (2008), "this is not another episode in a series for us," says Nolan.
p1039
aV"It\u2019s the third act in one large story."
p1040
aVIt also lands as the third act of a superhero summer, the last of three blockbusters after Marvel\u2019s The Avengers and The Amazing Spider-Man.
p1041
aVAs an action movie with physical and emotional heft, The Dark Knight Rises would appear to be the heavyweight contender.
p1042
aVBut The Avengers vaulted past the Potter, Pirates and Transformers franchises to become the third-highest-grossing movie in history after Avatar and Titanic, reaping a worldwide box office of $1.4 billion.
p1043
aVTough act to follow\u2014even though The Dark Knight earned over $1 billion.
p1044
aVTwenty years ago, who could have predicted that Hollywood would be a comic-book kingdom?
p1045
aVBlame it on Tim Burton\u2019s Batman (1989), which spawned a breed of dark, operatic spectacles for grown-up fanboys.
p1046
aVNow every self-respecting star needs a franchise and a mask, while comic-book culture ravages the ecology of the multiplex like an invasive species.
p1047
aVBut Nolan doesn\u2019t see his work as part of the trend.
p1048
aV"We never saw our films as comic-book movies," he says.
p1049
aV"The jumping-off point for Batman Begins was to make a movie, like any other adaptation."
p1050
aVYet he realizes that Rises\u2019 anchor spot in this superhero summer will affect its fate.
p1051
aV"How it\u2019s going to do, I have no idea," says the 41-year-old British director.
p1052
aV"All I can do is make the best film I can and hope people go along for the ride."
p1053
aVThere is a lot riding on it.
p1054
aVEverything about The Dark Knight Rises seems to be an escalation of scale.
p1055
aVWith an estimated budget of $250 million, it clocks in at a mighty two hours, 44 minutes.
p1056
aVHalf the movie was filmed in the giant IMAX format, while the rest was shot on 70-mm and 35-mm film.
p1057
aVStubbornly old-school, Nolan refused to use digital video or 3D.
p1058
aVAnd he often chose bravura stunts over computer graphics\u2014from men dangling off a plane to 11,000 extras watching a football game as the field erupts with explosives.
p1059
aV"Audiences are ruthless in their demand for freshness and novelty," says Nolan.
p1060
aV"They don\u2019t want to see the same thing again and again.
p1061
aVThey need to see it done in a different way and in a different place.
p1062
aVIt\u2019s a particular challenge with a sequel because you want familiar elements."
p1063
aVAlong with Caine, they include Gary Oldman and Morgan Freeman who return as Wayne\u2019s two other father figures, Commissioner Gordon and his CEO Lucius Fox, respectively.
p1064
aV("He\u2019s got a lot of fathers for an orphan," Nolan concedes.)
p1065
aVBut he has two new divas to play with: Hathaway\u2019s cat burglar Selina Kyle and philanthropist Miranda Tate (Marion Cotillard).
p1066
aVThe Dark Knight Rises picks up the story eight years after The Dark Knight.
p1067
aVHaving taken the fall for the death of district attorney Harvey Dent, Batman has vanished.
p1068
aVBruce Wayne, the tycoon behind the cowl, is now a bearded recluse who walks with a cane, holed up in Wayne Manor like a Gotham Howard Hughes.
p1069
aVWhen a ferocious new villain named Bane (Tom Hardy) lays siege to his financial empire, he hauls the batsuit out of storage.
p1070
aV(It\u2019s surprising how little screen time it gets\u2014first we wait for Batman\u2019s return, and later, while Wayne is imprisoned in a pit, we wait for him to rise again.)
p1071
aVScarred by a horrific injury (what comic-book villain isn\u2019t?
p1072
aV), Bane is masked by a contraption that pumps him with painkillers\u2014though its main effect is to turn his accented voice into an unearthly growl while channelling shades of Hannibal Lecter and Blue Velvet\u2019s Dennis Hopper.
p1073
aVBane\u2019s dialogue could benefit from subtitles, especially since he has to explain so much of the plot.
p1074
aVBatman\u2019s voice is distorted, too, so when they converse it\u2019s like listening to talking dogs.
p1075
aVNo matter: in the end, it all comes down to a fist fight.
p1076
aVThis time Batman is not just fighting crime, but saving his city from annihilation.
p1077
aVUnlike Heath Ledger\u2019s Joker, who picked off victims one by one for sheer sport, Bane is a terrorist on a doomsday mission, armed with a nuclear device stolen from Wayne Industries.
p1078
aV"That was an important part of giving this film the scale it needed," says Nolan.
p1079
aV"When you\u2019re just stuck in Gotham, there\u2019s a danger things start to feel a bit village-y."
p1080
aVBetween the spectre of epic terrorism and the allure of lethal women, there\u2019s more of a James Bond feel to this Batman opus than the others.
p1081
aV"But it\u2019s been there throughout," says Nolan.
p1082
aV"We\u2019ve been shamelessly plundering the Bond movies that I loved growing up.
p1083
aVIt would be more obvious if it had an English character at the head.
p1084
aVThis is a very American story."
p1085
aVEven if this Brit director has stocked it with Brit actors\u2014Bale, Caine, Oldman and Hardy.
p1086
aV"You go for the right people for the job," he says, "and they turn out to be English."
p1087
aVThe pedigree of the cast imparts automatic gravitas.
p1088
aVAnd unlike so many comic-book movies, from Iron Man to The Avengers, Nolan\u2019s work is not a maze of jokey, postmodern asides.
p1089
aVThese are action movies freighted with dramatic and intellectual ambition.
p1090
aVHathaway\u2019s Catwoman may come on like a Bond girl, an agent of comic and erotic relief, but she has a subversive agenda.
p1091
aV"There\u2019s a storm coming," she tells Wayne.
p1092
aV"You and your friends better batten down the hatches, because when it hits, you\u2019re all gonna wonder how you ever thought you could live so large and leave so little to the rest of us."
p1093
aVSound like Occupy Wall Street?
p1094
aVNolan did just that when he used 1,000 extras to film a pitched battle between cops and mercenaries in Manhattan.
p1095
aV"When we went to Wall Street to film, the Occupy movement had grown up around it and there were ridiculous reports we had chosen it for that reason.
p1096
aVBut it took a year of planning, and the scene had been written two years before that."
p1097
aVWhile 9/11 casts a long shadow over Gotham\u2019s scenes of terrorist destruction, the Occupy echoes are prescient.
p1098
aVNolan "had no way of knowing," says Bale.
p1099
aVFilming just blocks from the protest, he recalls, "I was looking at him\u2014how did you know?"
p1100
aVGotham, explains Nolan, "is a parallel world, and you wind up mirroring the concerns of the time."
p1101
aVOne concern among those who care about cinema is that it\u2019s being overrun by comic-book franchises: the masked superhero has usurped the face of the movie star as Hollywood\u2019s most powerful icon.
p1102
aVWhich Nolan doesn\u2019t dispute.
p1103
aV"We\u2019re definitely well into a phase where our actors are not willing to brand themselves as movie stars the way actors of the past did," he says.
p1104
aV"When you look at a guy like Christian, whether he\u2019s wearing a mask or not, this is one of our great actors.
p1105
aVBut he wants to be different in every film.
p1106
aVHe doesn\u2019t want the audience to go to a Christian Bale movie; he wants them to come see the character he\u2019s playing.
p1107
aVThat\u2019s true of most leading men working today.
p1108
aVThat wasn\u2019t true 20 years ago."
p1109
aVNolan and Bale say they are both done with Batman\u2014although The Dark Knight Rises ends on a note that will allow another filmmaker to pick up the franchise where they left off.
p1110
aVBut Nolan, still a force behind Hollywood\u2019s superhero hegemony, is producing next year\u2019s Superman reboot, Man of Steel.
p1111
aVThe key to comic-book material, he insists, is to treat it as "a source for movies of different types, not a genre\u2014if the comic-book movie is a genre, like the western, the audience will want something different."
p1112
aVAs for his own directing future, "I have no idea where I\u2019m going next," says Nolan.
p1113
aVDown the road, a Bond movie would not be out of the question.
p1114
aVAnd he doesn\u2019t even rule out 3D, if it\u2019s appropriate.
p1115
aV"I\u2019m all about choice," he declares.
p1116
aV"I don\u2019t like being told the way I should make a film."
p1117
aVFor one of the few filmmakers who can stand up to the studios, that may be the ultimate Hollywood superpower\u2014the ability to say no.
p1118
aV The answer continues to be "no."
p1119
aV"The Dark Knight Rises" is a magnificent way to close out an exciting trilogy.
p1120
aVAfter eight years of self-imposed exile, the caped crusader (Christian Bale) deals with an urban terrorist called Bane (Tom Hardy. )
p1121
aVBatman\u2019s alter ego, Bruce Wayne, hides away in Wayne Manor, but no longer.
p1122
